{{Infobox language |name=Gweno |nativename=''Kigweno'' |states=[[Tanzania]] |region=North Pare Mountains, Kilimanjaro Region |speakers=?<!--"moribund" contradicts claim that ethnic and speaker pop are the same--> |speakers2=(older adults)<ref name=e18>{{e18|gwe}}</ref> |ethnicity=2,200 (2006)<ref name=e18/><!-- removed in Ethnologue 19 --> |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam2=[[Atlantic–Congo languages|Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3=[[Benue–Congo languages|Benue–Congo]] |fam4=[[Bantoid languages|Bantoid]] |fam5=[[Bantu languages|Bantu]] |fam6=[[Northeast Bantu]] |fam7=Chaga–Taita |fam8=[[Chaga languages|Chaga]] |iso3=gwe |glotto=gwen1239 |glottorefname=Gweno |guthrie=E.65 |script=Unwritten }}
'''Gweno''' is a [[Bantu language]] spoken in the [[Pare Mountains|North Pare Mountains]] in the [[Kilimanjaro Region]] of [[Tanzania]]. The people known as the Gweno (or more properly ''Asu''<ref name="Phillipson">{{cite web|title = Gweno, a little known Bantu language of Northern Tanzania|url = http://www.ddl.ish-lyon.cnrs.fr/fulltext/Philippson/Philippson_2000.pdf|publisher = CNWS Publications|last = Phillipson|first = Gerard|last2 = Nurse|first2 = Derek}}</ref>) are a [[Chaga]] ethnic and linguistic group. Since the Chaga people are [[Bantu languages|Bantu]] speakers, the adopted language contains dialects similar to that of the Kenyan language [[Kamba language|Kamba]]. Gweno shares about 54% to 56% of its vocabulary with other Chaga dialects and 46% with Taita dialects. However, a large percentage of its vocabulary is not seen in the other dialects.<ref name="unesco.org">{{Cite web|url=http://portal.unesco.org/ci/en/ev.php-URL_ID=10500&URL_DO=DO_TOPIC&URL_SECTION=201.html|title=Gweno: UNESCO-CI|website=portal.unesco.org|access-date=2017-02-10}}</ref> Also at the start of the 11th century, the Chaga people descended and migrated from the Bantu group in which they migrated to the foothills of mount Kilimanjaro. The Gweno language is today spoken mostly by older adults, with younger generations having shifted to [[Pare language|Asu]] and [[Swahili language|Swahili]].<ref name="e18" /> ''Ethnologue'' considers Gweno to be moribund;<ref name="e18" /> the language is not being passed down because children have not been exposed to Gweno since the 1970s.<ref name="unesco.org" /> The generational shift from Gweno to either Asu or Swahili has certainly created shifts in dialect, however Gweno speakers do not see this as a threat.<ref name="Phillipson" />
