{{Infobox language | name = Masalit | nativename = kana masalaka/masaraka | states = [[Sudan]], [[Chad]] | region = [[West Darfur]], [[South Darfur]] ([[Sudan]]), [[Ouaddaï Region]] ([[Chad]]) | ethnicity = [[Masalit people|Masalit]] | speakers = 440,000 | date = 2011-2013 | ref = <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/mls|title=Masalit|work=Ethnologue|access-date=2018-09-14|language=en}}</ref> | familycolor = Nilo-Saharan | fam2 = [[Maban languages|Maban]] | fam3 = Masalit languages | lc1 = mls | ld1 = Masalit | lc2 = mdg | ld2 = Massalat | glotto = nucl1440 | glottoname = Nuclear Masalit | glotto2 = mass1262 | glottoname2 = Massalat }} '''Masalit''' (autonym ''Masala/Masara'') ({{Lang-ar|ماساليت}}) is a [[Maban language]] spoken by the [[Masalit people]] in western [[Darfur]], [[Sudan]].
The Masalit language has two [[sociolect]]s: "heavy" Masalit, spoken by higher-ranking people and those in the countryside, with a complicated [[agglutinative]] grammar, and "light", spoken particularly in the home and in the market, with a somewhat simplified grammatical structure and many borrowings from [[Sudanese Arabic]], the regional [[lingua franca]] and language of education.
A group of Masalit known as the ''Massalat'' moved west into central-eastern [[Chad]] and have almost entirely switched to [[Arabic]]. Their ethnic population in Chad was {{sigfig|29,800|2}} as of the 1993 census, but only 10 speakers of their language were reported in 1991.<ref name=e18>{{Ethnologue18|mls}}</ref>
