{{more citations needed|date=January 2018}}
'''Mikrani''' ({{IPAc-en|m|ɪ|ˈ|k|r|ɑː|n|i}}; [[Devanagari]]: मिकरानी, {{lang-ur|مکرانی}}) are a [[Muslim]] community found in the [[Sarlahi District|Sarlahi]] and [[Rautahat District|Rautahat]] districts of [[Nepal]], [[Bihar]], [[Uttar Pradesh]] and [[Gujarat]] in [[India]], [[Rajshahi]], [[Gaibandha District|Gaibandha]], [[Dinajpur District, Bangladesh|Dinajpur]], [[Old Dhaka]] in [[Bangladesh]] as well as in [[Pakistan]] and [[Afghanistan]].<ref>People of India Gujarat Volume XXI Part Two edited by R.B Lal, P.B.S.V Padmanabham, G Krishnan & M Azeez Mohideen pages 828–833</ref> They are also known as Mukeri, [[Makrani caste|Makrani]], Mekrani, Barmaki, Ranki and Muzkeri.<ref>People of India Uttar Pradesh Volume XLII Part Two edited by A Hasan & J C Das pages 995 to 999</ref> They belong to the [[Muker tribe]] and the Mikrani title is mostly used in [[Nepal]], [[India]] and [[Bangladesh]] while some also use Mukeri or Miya Mukeri.
==History and origin== The word ''Muker'' is said to have derived from [[Arabic]] ''makeri'', meaning those who helped in the construction of [[Mecca]]. They were initially called ''Makkai'', which referred to residents of [[Mecca]], which was later corrupted to ''makeri''. They are divided into two endogamous groups, the Mukeri and Shaikh Banjara. They rank themselves as [[Shaikhs in South Asia|Shaikh]]. The Shaikh Banjara are further divided into the Mikrani, Muqri, Barmaki, Siddiqui and Shaikh. Different groups have different traditions to their origin.
The Mukeri or Muker in [[Bihar]] and [[Nepal]] claim to be descendants of early [[Arab]] settlers, whose initial area of settlement in [[South Asia]] was the [[Makran]] region. According to their tradition they arrived in [[Bihar]] during the period of [[Khalji dynasty|Khalji]] ruler, and were initially known as Makrani, which was eventually shortened to Muker.<ref>People of India Bihar Volume XVI Part One edited by S Gopal & Hetukar Jha pages 692 to 693 Seagull Books</ref> They are found in [[Sarlahi]] district ([[Malangwa]], [[Bhadsar]], [[Masaili]], Khutauna, [[Simara, Sarlahi|Pakadi]], [[Murtiya]], [[Parsa District|Parsa]], [[Haripur, Janakpur|Haripur]], [[Lalbandi]], [[Hariyon]], [[Ishworpur]] villages) [[Rautahat]] district ([[Gaur]] and [[Rajdevi|kattarban]] villages).{{sfn|Niroula|1998}} They speak [[Urdu]], [[Nepali language|Nepali]] and the local [[Angika]] language.<ref>People of India Bihar Volume XVI Part One edited by S Gopal & Hetukar Jha pages 692 to 693 Seagull Books</ref> Those who lives in Bangladesh speaks in Bengali. Sarlahi district is the district of Nepal, where majority of Mikrani community lives.
==Tradition== The Muker were traditionally businessman, moving from place to place, selling goods. They historically traded scented [[oil]], aromatic goods, food grains, [[tobacco]], leather products and cattle. Many are now settled agriculturalists. The community are Muslim of the Sunni sect.<ref>People of India Uttar Pradesh Volume XLII Part Two edited by A Hasan & J C Das pages 995</ref> Some of the were the Islamic Dayee (inviter), a caller who notifies the others from dangers.
